The documentation for [Using pre-specified RSS feeds |http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Using+pre-specified+RSS+feeds] is misleading, particularly the following section:

bq. To subscribe to RSS feeds generated by Confluence, for a particular page (where available)

This gives the impression that users can subscribe to RSS on a page-level. However, Confluence can only subscribe to only certain pages which is not a Confluence page. For example, the Dashboard or when you click Dashboard > Browse space > Pages or Dashboard > Browse space > News

The search for documents that were changed yesterday does not work correctly. There are never displayed any results.

My guess is that the error is because of the following method in the DateRangeEnum:
{code:java}
YESTERDAY(1)
	{
		@Override
		public DateRangeQuery.DateRange dateRange()
		{
			Calendar c = getStartOfToday();
			c.add(Calendar.DAY_OF_YEAR, -1);
			Date startOfYesterday = c.getTime();
			Date beforeMidnightYesterday = new Date(c.getTime().getTime() - 1);
			return new DateRangeQuery.DateRange(startOfYesterday, beforeMidnightYesterday, true, true);
		}
	},
{code}

I think this results in an effective date range of exactly one millisecond. If you change the order of the lines as follows, the bug might be solved.

{code:java}
YESTERDAY(1)
	{
		@Override
		public DateRangeQuery.DateRange dateRange()
		{
			Calendar c = getStartOfToday();
			
			// this line should be here
			Date beforeMidnightYesterday = new Date(c.getTime().getTime() - 1);
			
			c.add(Calendar.DAY_OF_YEAR, -1);
			Date startOfYesterday = c.getTime();
			return new DateRangeQuery.DateRange(startOfYesterday, beforeMidnightYesterday, true, true);
		}
	},
{code}

